description.text: This is a stand for holding your tablet computer at a nice angle in portrait or landscape mode.  I designed it for a Samsung Galaxy 10.1 tablet but it also works for a iPad 2.

As show in the photo and models, this was printed with the stand on one side so it is very tall and skinny. I printed it on a Maker bot Replicator. It printed without a raft. The bed was set at 110c.  The stand took all day to print, about 7 hours.  With the 10% infill, it looked like a strange cross section of a bone.  I printed it in the white ABS that came with the new printer.  As printed, it is 5 inches tall (wide).  Everything worked fine except it developed a crack in the back along the layers.  The crack goes about halfway through but did not break the stand.  You could get around this by taking the SketchUp profile and only extruding it 2 inches and printing two of these.  I suspect it cracked because the previous layer cooled to much before the next layer was added.  I did the shell with a layer setting of 2.  It warped slightly off the bed but completed the print successfully.  I am including the Sketchup Model as printed and also the original profile in SketchUp in case you want to mod it before extruding to your desired height.

description.text: This thing was made with Tinkercad. Edit it online https://www.tinkercad.com/things/f0DiUmVHz6X

Since Orange Pi Zeros have an overheating issue (mine does), I figured I'd make a minimalized 'open air' tall case with a 25mm 5v DC fan mount to blow directly at the core processor.

Notes:

  • I included the original Sketchup file with an outline (on the top and bottom) showing where I think an alternate location for another fan mount may be. This file also includes the measurements I used (after making the top portion) to make the bottom, just in case anyone wants to redo the bottom.
  • The design uses 3mm screws/bolts.
  • The holes on the 'towers' are deliberately undersized (a bit) to help create a good thread when attached to the top.
  • It can be bolted from the top or bottom - change the hole sizes if needed.
  • The fan mount is for a generic 25mm fan, but I specifically use the 2510S 5V DC fan attached to pins 4 and 6 (on the OPi Zero pinout).
  • I added bottoms with a round and square vent/hole to further dissipate heat. Personally, I have mine bolted down by the top so the bottom rents up.

Notice: I include the Sketchup files for my posts to allow modding and any changes you want made. I generally do not take pictures of my creations and only show the isometric view from Sketchup, as each print will be different.

Happy printing and modding!

title: Lasercut Form and Facade Miniature Wargame Building
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This design was inspired by old mods I did to WH40K Epic buildings back in the day. Remember the Styrofoam building sets from that big box game, the ones with empty and hollow backs? I created multi-layer cardboard facades to cover those gaping chasms. Well, this is pretty much the same thing, but I used MDF as a basic building form and .05 inch chipboard card stock as facades. The thickness of card stock can probably vary, but don't go too thin or thick.

This template is suitable for ~10mm miniatures. Other scales and facades may follow, with me using MDF base forms like this one and possibly others. These are relatively cheap, quick and easy to build... if you have access to a "lasor" - 'cause it sure as hell beats cutting them by hand with an x-acto knife. The form was glued with Gorilla glue and the facade was applied with contact cement, but the fumes are atrocious, so I'd recommend the "green" contact cement if you can get it?

Designed with a minimum 0.5" safety margin around edge of the frame. The building form is formatted for cutting from a 3mm MDF 12" x 9" (Arch A) sheet. One Arch C (24" x 18") sheet, the size that fits across the bed of an Epilog Helix, should provide 4 MDF building forms. The facade template is formatted to 15" x 10" but I used 18" x 12" card stock from my local art store for the prototype cuts and build. I have provided the PDF and a SVG files that I converted online at https://cloudconvert.com/vsd-to-svg. Shared as is.

Effective 13MAY2017 I've added an updated/alternate facade template with additional facades including 1/3 and 1/2 width facades, if you wish to glue two or more buildings together to make a multi-unit building complex. Adjusted the template size from 10" x 15" to an Arch B size (12" x 18") because I found pads of 1.5mm chip board card stock at my local art supply store (http://www.richesonart.com/pdfs/papers.pdf).

If you are inclined to be more than a taker and a consumer, pay forward by contributing to this site, as so many others have before you, or perform a random act of kindness, or donate to a good cause when the opportunity next arises. And if you download this, please LIKE, it helps get the word out and spread these designs around. That is all.

title: Atom Kit for Visually Impaired
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is an atom kit based on a standard organic/inorganic molecule kit. Each atom is named according to its molecular geometry. Central atoms all are differentiated by different textured shapes used as skins of the typical spherical atom. It is inspired by the Envision the Future Design Challenge submissions of Flowerto found here: https://pinshape.com/items/35137-3d-printed-tactile-chemistry-learning-atoms and a design inspired by Caroline Benz, and undergraduate student at Marymount University https://pinshape.com/items/35147-3d-printed-atom-kit-for-visually-impaired.

The design was created as consulting work for a university.

Holes for pegs are 5 mm, to make them compatible with bonds that are often found in molecule kits.

Samples of the textures are also included, so they can be printed separately and combined with braille for helping teach visually impaired users the representations for the various atoms. This is based on the tactile chemistry kit from the Envision the Future Challenge: https://pinshape.com/items/35137-3d-printed-tactile-chemistry-learning-atoms

I found the tactile elements of that kit weren't printing well on a variety of printers so redid the concept from scratch in fusion 360/meshmixer.

An color-coded excel table listing the atoms, bond geometries and textures used is included.

title: Kossel Pro Delta E3D V6 End Effector Version 8

description.text:
This is version 8 of my end effector for the openbeam kossel pro and other delta printers. It uses an E3D V6 and has fantastic part cooling.

Main goals for this end effector:
-fit an e3d v6
-avoid nozzle from getting too far beneath arms
-integrated hotend cooling
-great wrap around part cooling
-two piece hotend clamp
-standard 30mm fans
-no interference between end effector and arms
-secure arm mounting
-easily printable
-fan duct with ribbing to direct air
-fan duct nozzle close to print nozzle

Improvements from version 5:
-improved part cooling ducting for more airflow
-two piece hotend clamp
-more secure arm mounting- eliminates the round standoff
-easier to print- eliminated areas with small contact to the bed
-fan duct body allows for greater airflow
-fan duct body is further away from heater block to prevent melting/warping
-fan duct with ribbing to direct air
-fan duct nozzle close to print nozzle

Hardware List:
8x M3 4x4mm embedded nuts
M3 screws: 1x 6mm, 2x 8mm, 2x 10mm
6x 5/8" #4 thread rolling screws to mount fans

Print with supports set to 46 degrees to avoid support in hard to reach places
For the fan duct, set extrusion width to .5mm, layer height to .1mm, and print super slow (30mm/s) to be able to print the overhangs properly with no support.

Note that you might have to edit the Start-Code to accommodate your printer setup!

M190 S55 ; Set Bed Temperature (default 55°C)
M104 T0 S195 ; Set Extruder Temperature (default 195°C)
M109 T0 S195 ; Set Extruder Temperature and Wait (default 195°C)

For best possible print results you may want to use this cooler if you have an Anet A8 printer: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2121279

Let me know how it turned out.

Leo

description.text:
Spool adaptor to fit the Creality spool arm to prevent the spool from tumbling and cause under-extrusion.

I made this because when I adjusted my extruder steps per mm, I tested the impact of the counter drag from the spool which turned out to cause massive under extrusion.

The impact was about 1-2mm of under extrusion, especially when the extruder pulls the filament enough to initiate a spool revolution but then retracts and refeed again, the spool would bounce, causing quite a pull and lead to incomplete refeed.

Beware that I havent "tested" this all that much yet as I just made one print and put it to use, but so far it seems to work quite well.

If you use this, please let me know if you encounter any problems so I can fix it and update the download on here.

The tube part has a length of 80mm and an inner diameter of 31.3mm.
The conical end pieces are 45-55mm.

title: Reuleaux tetrahedron - Solid of "almost" constant width (OpenSCAD)

description.text:
After watching Angus video, I got curious and decided to experiment with the concept of "solid of constant width".
https://youtu.be/2eUWT9cI23o

I implemented it based on a tetrahedron.

[Update 06/05/2017]: It turns out that this shape is called a Reuleaux tetrahedron, and it's NOT a shape of constant width. It has a slight extra width between 2 opposite edges. The popular solution to make it constant width is to implement the Meissner tetrahedra. The mathematician in me doesn't like that none-symmetrical shape. It looks like a patched shape. I'm pretty sure we can apply "half" the correction to all 6 edges to make a symmetrical shape. I will have to do more studies on the subject and understand the math before trying to implement it.
According to this paper, the shape I'm trying to implement is called a Spheroform tetrahedron:
http://www.xtalgrafix.com/Reuleaux/Spheroform%20Tetrahedron.pdf
I found an OpenSCAD implementation on Thingiverse:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:408157

title: Universal Cantilevered Spool Holder for 3D printers

description.text:
Hanging a filament spool on a horizontal axis is the most common way to attach material to a 3D printer. Since there is a variety of different spool sizes on the market, we designed this spool holder to be compatible with as many different 3D printer models as possible.

All 3D files for the main spool holder parts can be 3D-printed flat on the build plate without the need for support structures. We also designed several accessories and adaptors to make this spool holder compatible with various 3D printer models.

The spool holder axle consists of two symmetrical halves which are held together in the front by a lock fitting, and in the rear via the butterfly joint used in our Modular Castle Playset. (thingiverse.com/thing:1930665).

This project was created by Tim Wahlström in cooperation with the 3D-team at CreativeTools.se in Sweden.

3D printing

If you have a 3D printer with a 3D print volume of 150 mm or larger, you can print the file 01-MAIN__COMPLETE_BUILDPLATE, which contains all the main parts for the spool holder. The files named 01-MAIN... are the individual spool holder parts. All the remaining files are accessories.

Advantages

  • Easy to print.
  • Narrow design fits many 3D printers.
  • The thin shaft fits spools with smaller core dimensions.
  • Two-step attachment depth allows for thin- and thick-gauged 3D printer cases.
  • Symmetrical halves allow for supportless 3D printing.
  • Adapters for mounting on arbitrary vertical and horizontal surfaces.

Assembly

Please refer to the following video for instructions.

  • https://youtu.be/eLwj2bMxoe4

Feedback and adaptors

If this spool holder does not fit onto your 3D printer model, please write a comment to let us know. Your feedback is highly appreciated!

By Creative Tools

List of compatible 3D printer models

If this spool holder fits your 3D printer, and it isn't listed below, please let us know in the comments so we can add it to the list. We highly appreciate your feedback!

Recommendations

We highly recommend you to make sure that the filament entering the extruder is clean from dust. It will prolong the life of your extruder and make the printer more reliable.

Therefore, we designed the filament filter and lubricator, which you can download from the link below.

description.text:
These are accessories for upgrading to a 5mm Z-rod, The reduction of edge waviness, makes the conversion a must have, both items have been printed with a 5mm z-rod and the quality speaks for itself. Make sure to properly update the firmware based on the thread count, the reason there is such a difference in quality is both the number of steps per millimeter of height increase increasing the accuracy, while the step counts become a evenly divisible number as opposed to the use of US standard converter to metric. Required parts are;

title: Battery Adapter, AA to C cell
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
We needed to power up a piece of surveillance equipment, but it took C cell batteries and all the ones we had were dead.  So using the Swiss army knife that is the 3D printer, we made some nice adapters that allow you to insert AA batteries into any device that's designed to accept C cells!  The voltage is the same, so no worries there, but certain high-current devices might not like the higher equivalent series resistance (ESR) of the AA versus the C cell.  For low-current applications, this should do just fine.  
Two versions of the adapter are included.  The first version, upon printing, was discovered to be a bit too snug around the AA.  This may vary by 3D printer and materials, so we're including it anyway.  We still managed to get the AA in there with a few taps from a hammer.  The second version is 0.2mm wider on the internal diameter, so it did not require any hammering to get the AA in.  We suggest printing version 2, and if the AA fits too loosely inside of it, try version 1.  
Have fun!  
~ Peter
Printed successfully on a 3D Systems Cube in neon green PLA.

comments.text: Nice simple idea. Printed one on an Up! mini using ABS, quick print 0.35mm z-res, but even the larger one was too tight for an AA. Ended up drafting a quick one in FreeCAD, 48mm long OD=26.2mm ID=14.6mm which worked like a charm. Just enough friction to hold the battery in place but can still be removed.

This is my first spinner design, so I'm marking it as a work in progress, although I've made a couple and they seem to work fine. I wanted to make a design that didn't have exposed bearings or other hardware, so I went with a design that has 5/16" nuts sandwiched between two halves. This makes it thicker than most spinners, but it will spin really well -- especially with ceramic bearings. (Obviously, you'll need to supply one of the usual skateboard bearings that are used in this kind of spinner.)

The two halves of the spinner are mirror images of each other, so they'll fit together after you add the nuts. I would glue the nuts to one half first, then glue the other half on top. I added a small dot above one of the indentations on the bottom to help you orient the halves, since they need to go together in a specific way. Just match up the dots on both halves. If you want the two-color look like I have in the photo, you can change filament colors at around the 85% point (just make sure that the interior details have started to print before switching).

title: Makerbot TOM Heated Light Box Mod (Idea)

description.text: My 12cm fan does a great job sucking out the fumes, but this introduces some cooling issues during large builds. Items tend to split between layers toward the end of the build. This is my solution to the problem...the Lighted Box Mod.

Essentially, this enclosed the sides of the TOM with and array of good ol' fashioned vintage christmas lights (the larger hot ones). These incandescent bulbs burn hot enough to nearly catch a christmas tree on fire, thusly heating the chamber to a comforatble build tempature, fast enough to keep up with the cooling fan, which exhausts the ABS air (fumes).
Im thinking only about 3-4 bulbs per layer, centered on each side of the chamber should be enough, at about 4 layers total. As the Z platform rises, it would trigger these bulbs to light up, layer by layer, as the print grows. This would be via physical switches or perhaps Rep G code.
Only issues are that these bulbs run at 110VAC and need to see if they can still generate enough heat a lower voltage (hopefully 24VAC). Also I need to find the equipment to turn on each layer of HVAC lights via (probably) relays.
Thoughts?

description.text:
Simple and light z axis for eleksmaker laser chassis, will need a 3 axis controller retrofitted.
Uses a 28BYJ-48 motor for Z motion and a motor from an el-cheapo 3.6V engraver I had lying around with a dead battery.

Axis sliders are 50mm each of 1/8 brass rod I had as well and 25mm of a larger tube that snug fit over it, outside diameter is 4mm, I melted the rods into the ends and tubes into the "motor mount".

A single bearing is used to act as a cam, a 3x10x4, could probably just print a circle to do the job.
The cam was also designed to have a brass 3mm insert melted into it to act as the bearing spacer.

Total motion is 10mm, I am using the supplied LM2003 for testing as motor is still unipolar 5 wire, will be removing the centre wire and cuttng the track internally to make it a bipolar and using it with an extra Pololu as a Z axis on grbl.

assembly.stl shows the parts orientation, kit.stl should print a full kit (untested)

rsdocs.zip contains the designspark mechanical buld files if you want to modify anything.

Hot melt glue was used to attach the slider to the bracket instead of a more permanent glue, also a couple of blobs of hot melt on the end of the cam_follower hold it to the motor mount.

My motor is 12v and needs around 2044 steps/rev.

VERSION 3 files added, after some testing I found the original low voltage motor had insufficient torque drilling and was badly balanced.
So I dismantled everything and reassembled with an old DJI drone motor, I had to turn the prop thread down to 5mm and drilled and tapped the same collet assembly from the low voltage motor which now screws to the 5mm thread.
Surprisingly it is fairly straight.

Hardware mods mean I now needed a different mount plat for the motor bottom and a larger hole in the bottom 'brace' to allow the motor to pass through, so added the 2 new parts. (photo of it fitted above with the brushless motor)

I used the existing 'cam follower' part but snipped off the bottom nug and filed it down to fit in the 4mm square hole on the motor bottom part.

Plan is to use the standard 30A ESC from the 12V rail and feed the servo from the servo connector on the Eleksmaker Mana SE board, however grbl will need some hacking to produce a suitable servo signal, I may find it easier to generate a servo pulse on a completely unrelated and unused pin. temporarily I can spin up the motor with a servo tester.

you need the four parts listed in the " thing details" three of them I've modded myself and those you will find in the thing files the fourth part is from https://grabcad.com/library/mk2_40mm_fan_duct-1 and the stl file is there.. I didn't mod it at all but it's a really hard print.. I found the only way I could print it properly was to flip it 90º onto its side, so the internal web was vertical then manually add external supports only in simplify 3D.. but all that along with the spacer etc is so you can fit a near silent 40mm fan to the hotend cooler.. if you JUST want the dual layer cooling just print the axial fan mount mk6 and you need to cut the original prusa hotend cover off flush with top of the hotend itself.. the fan I used for that axial mount is multicomp mc36285 althought i've discovered for reasons i've not yet worked out this fan is either 100% on or it's off... it won't run at half speed like the original fan.... so I might look into that but frankly i've printed PLA (which is always 100% fan anyway) and I've printed flexible AND PETG with the fan blowing 100% and prints perfectly for me.. zero issues at all.. it's a 20mm thick fan shifts almost 8cfm ...and its quiet.. if you want to go the whole nine yards like i did you will need the spacer,the duct from grabcad ( i'll add his stl here in a minute to simplify things) and the fan I have is a sanace 40x40 109P0412H901 this matches the original 30x30 almost exactly both for airflow cfm AND the all important STATIC airflow.. it's also silent .. the z axis brace was directly made from here https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1656945... with sound and vibration insulating feet from here https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2205774/#files with the speaker isolation units via ebay http://www.ebay.co.uk/itm/OEHLBACH-Shock-Absorber-Resonanzd%C3%A4mpfer-Schockabsorber-schwarz-4-St%C3%BCck-55138/232234247012?ssPageName=STRK%3AMEBIDX%3AIT&_trksid=p2057872.m2749.l2649

author: BP1993

title: Circuit Playground Express Case with NeoPixel holes

description.text:
I'm hoping to hang a Circuit Playgound on the wall of my stairwell as a nightlight. The case Adafruit designed is great (love the smiley face!), but I needed a hole in the base to put a nail through and holes in the lid so that the NeoPixels can shine.

This is my first 3D design and the print turned out okay, but I think it still needs a little work. I'm worried that the lid will be a little thin. BUT, some paint and a little sticky-tack and it works great as a first effort.

Printer Brand:

FlashForge

Printer:

Creator Pro

I dragged the existing designs into Tinkercad and got things looking right. Lining up the NeoPixel holes was guess work at this point.

Next I pulled the 3D model of the Circuit Playground in and lined it up with the top to make sure my holes matched the NeoPixels perfectly. Having a properly scaled model of the actual hardware made modifying the case very straightforward!
